<%# Phase 29 (settings refactor) — settings security modal.

    A layout-positioned `<dialog>` with a `<turbo-frame>` inside; the
    `settings-modal` Stimulus controller wraps the dialog and swaps the
    target URL into the frame's `src` on open. Mirrors the
    `notification-modal` / `calendar-entry-modal` pattern.

    Each link that opens this modal carries:
      - `href`           — the canonical standalone URL (JS-off fallback).
      - `data-action`    — `click->settings-modal#open`.
      - optional `data-settings-modal-title-param` for the header.

    The standalone settings views (`/settings/security/totp`,
    `/settings/sessions`, `/settings/security/blocks`) are also wrapped
    in a matching `<turbo-frame id="settings_modal_frame">` so the
    server response slots into this frame cleanly.

    Phase 32 (Concern 2). Two optional locals:
      * `auto_open_url` (String or nil) — when set, the controller
        opens the dialog on connect and points the Turbo Frame at
        the URL. Used by the mandatory-2FA gate to auto-open the
        TOTP enrollment view.
      * `non_dismissible` (Boolean) — when true, the controller
        suppresses Escape, click-outside, and the close button. The
        bracketed [close] link is also omitted from the header so
        there is no surface to dismiss the dialog. %>
<%
  auto_open_url   = local_assigns.fetch(:auto_open_url, nil)
  non_dismissible = local_assigns.fetch(:non_dismissible, false)
  # 2026-05-16 polish — in non-dismissible (mandatory-2FA) mode the
  # enrollment view's body renders its own <h1> heading. The partial
  # used to pre-populate the header's <h2> with a duplicate copy of
  # the same text, which produced two stacked "two-factor setup
  # required" labels in the dialog. The header slot now stays empty
  # in mandatory mode — the view-body <h1> is the sole heading. The
  # <h2> element itself is kept so the standard modal flow (which
  # writes into it via `data-settings-modal-title-param`) still has
  # a target.
  default_title   = nil
  # 2026-05-16 polish — the standard settings dialog clamps the inner
  # wrapper to `max-width: 880px` (inline style). In non-dismissible
  # (mandatory-2FA) mode the enrollment view renders two `.pane` cells
  # side-by-side (2 × 444 = 888px) inside a widened 960px dialog. The
  # inline 880px cap minus the wrapper's 32px horizontal padding leaves
  # only 848px of usable content width — short of the 888px the two
  # panes need — so the second pane wraps below the first. Inline
  # styles win over external CSS, so the companion CSS rule at
  # `[data-settings-modal-non-dismissible-value="yes"] dialog.settings-modal > div`
  # cannot override an inline `max-width` without `!important`.
  #
  # 2026-05-16 scrollbar-flush polish — in mandatory mode the inner
  # wrapper used to cap at 928px while the dialog itself sits at 960px.
  # The inner is a block element with `width: 100%` clamped by
  # `max-width`; with no `margin: 0 auto` it left-aligns, so the
  # ~30px difference shows up as empty space on the right and the
  # inner's vertical scrollbar floats ~30px shy of the dialog's red
  # border. Lift the cap entirely in mandatory mode so the inner fills
  # the dialog's content area and the scrollbar sits flush with the
  # red border. The dialog's own 960px cap still bounds the wrapper;
  # the two 444px panes (888px) still fit inside the resulting
  # 960 - 32 = 928px of usable space, so the side-by-side layout the
  # turbo-frame block fix restored is preserved.
  #
  # 2026-05-16 dismissible-widening polish — when the dismissible
  # settings modal also widened to 960px (companion CSS rule
  # `dialog.settings-modal { max-width: 960px }`), the 880px inner
  # cap left an 80px empty gutter on the right of the dialog —
  # content sat left-aligned inside the wider frame. Lift the cap to
  # `none` for the dismissible case too so the inner fills the
  # dialog. Prose-heavy settings sub-pages now wrap at the same
  # 928px usable width the mandatory enrollment view uses, which is
  # already in production for the mandatory flow and reads fine in
  # monospace. Table-heavy sub-pages (sessions, blocks/locations)
  # get the full ~880px column area they need; the per-table scroll
  # rule in CSS handles narrower viewports.
  inner_max_width = "none"
%>
<%# 2026-05-16 structural fix #2 — the `settings-modal` Stimulus
    controller used to live on this `<dialog>` itself. That worked
    for the auto-open path (the controller's `connect()` runs as
    soon as the element enters the DOM, independent of ancestor
    relationships) and for the in-dialog actions
    (`click->...#clickOutside`, `[close]`, `cancel->...#cancelDismiss`),
    but it BROKE the trigger-link path. Trigger links in
    `_security_pane.html.erb` are siblings of the dialog under
    `settings/index.html.erb`, not descendants, so their click
    events never bubble through the dialog and Stimulus never fires
    `click->settings-modal#open`. The `<a href="…">` then fell
    through to default navigation and the page full-loaded instead
    of opening the modal.

    Fix: `data-controller="settings-modal"` and the two Stimulus
    value attributes now live on a wrapper `<div>` in
    `settings/index.html.erb` that encloses BOTH the panes (with
    the trigger links) AND this partial. The dialog keeps its
    target marker and its in-dialog actions; the wrapper owns the
    controller scope, so click events on any descendant — pane
    links OR `[close]` inside the dialog — reach the controller
    via normal event bubbling.

    `data-settings-modal-non-dismissible-value="…"` is still
    repeated on the dialog below — purely as a CSS hook. The
    companion selectors in `app/assets/tailwind/application.css`
    key on it to widen the dialog and adjust spacing in mandatory
    mode. Stimulus itself reads the value from the wrapper; the
    duplicate here is non-functional for JS. %>
<dialog data-settings-modal-target="dialog"
        data-settings-modal-non-dismissible-value="<%= non_dismissible ? "yes" : "no" %>"
        data-action="click->settings-modal#clickOutside cancel->settings-modal#cancelDismiss"
        class="pane-dialog settings-modal">
  <div style="padding: 12px 16px; min-width: 0; width: 100%; max-width: <%= inner_max_width %>; max-height: 80vh; overflow-y: auto;">
    <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between; margin-bottom: 8px;">
      <h2 data-settings-modal-target="title" style="margin: 0;"><%= default_title || raw("&nbsp;") %></h2>
      <% unless non_dismissible %>
        <%= render(BracketedLinkComponent.new(label: t("common.actions.close"), href: "#",
            data: { action: "click->settings-modal#close" })) %>
      <% end %>
    </div>
    <%# 2026-05-16 — inline `display: block; width: 100%` as a safety
        net alongside the global `turbo-frame { display: block }` rule
        in `app/assets/tailwind/application.css`. Custom elements
        default to `display: inline`, which shrinks the frame to its
        children's min-content and collapses the inner pane-row to
        one pane wide. The CSS rule is the proper fix; the inline
        style guarantees correct layout even if the rule is missed
        (specificity collision, build cache, etc.). %>
    <%= turbo_frame_tag "settings_modal_frame",
                        style: "display: block; width: 100%;",
                        data: { settings_modal_target: "frame" } %>
  </div>
</dialog>
